Argumentative writing often utilizes complex sentences with multiple clauses and connectors like "while," "whereas," and "if...then"

A strong argument must be supported by content, which is the "mainstay" of any presentation

Arguments can be structured by placing the strongest point at the beginning, middle, or end

discourse markers such as "on the one hand," "point of view," and "in view of"

Creating a synopsis—an "overview" similar to looking at a city from a rooftop—is the most critical first step

A good synopsis should define the topic and include dimensions, evidence, and illustrations

connectors and discourse markers (e.g., "nevertheless," "regardless," "therefore")
